teachers, businesses, employees,

00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:14.860
folks like you and me, we can
all create our own VR tours

00:28:14.860 --> 00:28:17.261
and easily share them
anywhere on the web.

00:28:20.150 --> 00:28:22.580
When you go to Tour
Creator, you start out

00:28:22.580 --> 00:28:26.790
by starting a new tour
or picking up on a draft.

00:28:26.790 --> 00:28:29.870
And then you add some basic
metadata, things like a title,

00:28:29.870 --> 00:28:34.560
description, category,
and a cover photo.

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:36.590
And then you fill
your tour with scenes.

00:28:36.590 --> 00:28:39.980
Scenes are made possible
through the use of 360 photos.

00:28:39.980 --> 00:28:42.810
Now if you have your
own 360 photos, awesome.

00:28:42.810 --> 00:28:45.110
You can upload them in
just a couple of clicks.

00:28:45.110 --> 00:28:46.940
But if you don't, have no fear.

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:48.840
We've integrated directly
with Street View.

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:51.230
So you can take advantage
of the massive library

00:28:51.230 --> 00:28:56.390
of 360 photos already
available in Google Maps.

00:28:56.390 --> 00:28:58.340
Once you add your
scenes, you add what

00:28:58.340 --> 00:29:00.140
we call points of interest.

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:02.000
These are essentially
areas of importance

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.380
that you'd like to highlight.

00:29:03.380 --> 00:29:05.480
And you can add a little
bit of text information

00:29:05.480 --> 00:29:08.480
to inform your viewer.

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:10.640
You can also enrich
these points of interest

00:29:10.640 --> 00:29:13.130
with other media like 2D photos.

00:29:13.130 --> 00:29:15.710
And in the future, we'll be
adding narration and ambient

00:29:15.710 --> 00:29:20.394
audio to help your viewers feel
like they're actually there.

00:29:20.394 --> 00:29:22.060
Now when you're done
creating your tour,

00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:23.326
you publish it to the web.

00:29:23.326 --> 00:29:24.700
You can make it
public for anyone

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:29.510
to see or unlisted so only
those with the link can see it.

00:29:29.510 --> 00:29:31.040
And when you publish
it to the web,

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:33.500
you actually publish it to Poly.

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:35.270
If you're not
familiar with Poly,

00:29:35.270 --> 00:29:38.000
Poly is Google's
library of 3D content

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:39.800
launched late last year.

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:43.490
Previously, Poly had things
like 3D models, 3D sketches,

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:47.390
and as of today, Poly will
also contain 3D experiences

00:29:47.390 --> 00:29:49.790
in the form of tours.

00:29:49.790 --> 00:29:52.100
And this is where the true
beauty of this product

00:29:52.100 --> 00:29:53.180
comes in.

00:29:53.180 --> 00:29:55.520
Because you're publishing
your tour to the web,

00:29:55.520 --> 00:29:58.460
all you need to do to
share it is share a URL.

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:01.250
So that means you can view
your tour in 2D on desktop

00:30:01.250 --> 00:30:02.960
or on your laptop computer.

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:05.895
You can text a link to your
tour to a friend or colleague.

00:30:05.895 --> 00:30:07.520
They can load it on
their mobile device

00:30:07.520 --> 00:30:10.610
and simply use Magic
Window to experience it,

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:12.650
or they can tap an
Enter VR button,

00:30:12.650 --> 00:30:15.170
put it in a Google
Cardboard, and immediately be

00:30:15.170 --> 00:30:19.080
immersed in the tour
that you just created.

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:21.540
Now you may be wondering,
what is this magic?

00:30:21.540 --> 00:30:22.970
I thought when it
came to VR, you

00:30:22.970 --> 00:30:24.590
have to install a
bunch of apps, get

00:30:24.590 --> 00:30:26.992
some really expensive hardware.

00:30:26.992 --> 00:30:29.450
